              spectral method. One uses a weak formulation of the equations of
              motion, which are solved on a mesh of hexahedral elements that is
              adapted to the free surface and to the main internal
              discontinuities of the model. The wavefield on the elements is
              discretized using high-degree Lagrange interpolants, and
              integration over an element is accomplished based upon the
              Gauss--Lobatto--Legendre integration rule. This combination of
              discretization and integration results in a diagonal mass matrix,
              which greatly simplifies the algorithm. We illustrate the great
              potential of the method by comparing it to a discrete
              wavenumber/reflectivity method for layer-cake models. Both body and
              surface waves are accurately represented, and the method can handle
              point force as well as moment tensor sources. For a model with very
              steep surface topography we successfully benchmark the method
              against an approximate boundary technique. For a homogeneous medium
              with strong attenuation we obtain excellent agreement with the
              analytical solution for a point force.},
