  abstract = {A common approach to the numerical solution of time-dependent
              partial differential equations, akin to the classical method of
              lines, is to discretize in space using a finite-difference or
              finite-element method and leave time as a continuous variable. This
              semidiscretization yields an initial-value problem for a system of
              ordinary differential equations for the solution of which there
              exists a wide choice of numerical techniques. The purpose of this
              paper is to survey methods of order greater than two for the
              integration of semidiscrete formulations of parabolic problems,
              especially diffusion problems. The formulae discussed fall into
              four classes, those based on rational approximation techniques,
              Runge-Kutta formulae, multistep formulae, and formulae based on
              some form of extrapolation. The main emphasis of this paper is on
              results concerning stability and order, and the computational
              efficiency of the various formulae in terms of matrix
              decompositions and back substitutions. Both linear and non-linear
              problems are discussed, although the emphasis is primarily on the
              linear problem, since it has received most attention in the
              literature.},
}

